fields.title: Staff Control
fields.text:
Start Session: Starts the session, and the subject screens will switch to the experiment's first phase.

Continue Session: Once all subjects have (optionally) completed the instructions, start the experiment. The instructions will be hidden, and the first period will start.

Start/Stop Timer: Once the experiment is started, press the Start Timer button to begin the clock. The clock runs inside the connection for the browser tab that pressed the Start Timer button. The clock will stop if that browser tab is refreshed or loses connection with the server. If this happens, press Stop Timer and then Start Timer to resume from the point the clock stopped. The experiment's progress is stored on the server and will not be lost.

Reset Connection Status: Sets all client connection statuses to "disconnected." Note that this will not disconnect any connected clients. This only changes the status. This will re-open all clients to auto connection.

Reset Session:  Remove all data and reset the experiment to the pre-start state. Warning: all data collected is destroyed.

Send Invitations:  Send an email to any subjects that have an email defined. The email will contain their private login link.

fields.title: Staff Data
fields.text:
All

  • Session ID: A unique ID number assigned to each session by the server.
  • Client #: Each subject in the experiment is assigned a client number based on the computer they are sitting at.
  • Label: The name given to each subject that is used to identify them from other subjects in the experiment.

Period Summary

  • Earnings: Earnings in cents this period.
  • Range End: Right edge of the subject's range.
  • Cherries Sent/Received: A record of cherries sent and taken from each person.

Actions:

  • Action
    • target_location_update: The subject moves to a new location.
    • chat: The subject talks to other subjects.
    • tractor_beam: The subject starts an interaction.
    • interaction: The subject completes an interaction.
    • help_doc: The subject views a help doc.
  • Info (Plain): Plain text info about the action
  • Info (JSON): The raw data related to that action.
  • Timestamp: UTC time the action was taken,

fields.title: Staff Subject List
fields.text:
Controls

Upload Email list: Enter a TAB, comma, and/or carriage return-separated list that will be loaded sequentially into the clients.  

Copy Earnings: Copy Student IDs and Earnings to the clipboard in an ESI Recruiter-compatible format.

Anonymize Data: Permanently remove the subject names, emails, and student IDs from the dataset.

 

Table

Client #:  Each client is numbered from 1 to 24.

ID Label: The label used to identify a person to others in the experiment.

Name: Subject's full name.

Student ID: Subject's student ID number.

Email: Email address to which to send private invitation links.

Earnings: Earnings in USD up to this point in the experiment.

Shareable Login Link: The unique link a person in the experiment uses to log in.

Connected: The client's connection status to the experiment.

Instruction: During the instruction phase, this shows the current instruction status for the subject.

Instructions View: View the instructions in a printable form from that person's perspective.

Login

Next available connection: Log in as the next available client who is not connected.  Note that a subject could log in multiple times by opening this link in multiple windows. This link auto-forwards to the Shareable Login Link defined above.

Login by client number: Log in as specified client by number.  Replace [client_number]" in the link with the desired client number ranging from 1 to 24.  Note that a person could log in as any client by changing the client_number. This link auto-forwards to the Shareable Login Link defined above.

fields.title: Staff Parameters General
fields.text:
Number of Periods: The total number of periods.

Period Length (seconds): The length of a period in seconds.

Break Frequency (periods): Every N period starts with an additional break phase where interactions are disabled.

Break Length (seconds): Length of the break phase.

Interaction Length (seconds): An interaction must be completed within this time before it is automatically closed.

Cool Down Length (seconds): The time a subject must wait before starting a new interaction.

Show Instructions: Start the experiment with an instruction phase.

Show Survey: Begin the experiment with a Qualtrics survey.

Prolific Mode: Run the session in Prolific compatibility mode.

Tokens per Period: The number of cherries available each period.

Token Value (¢): The value of a cherry in cents.

Interaction Range (Pixels): An avatar must be at least this close to start an interaction.

Avatar Scale: The size of an avatar.

Avatar Bounding Box Percent: The invisible box around an avatar that prevents overlapping.

Avatar Move Speed (pixels per second): The speed at which an avatar moves around the environment.

Avatar Animation Speed: The speed at which the avatar's animation runs when in motion.

World Width (pixels): The total width of the environment.

World Height (pixels): The total height of the environment.

Test Mode: The avatars will take random actions for testing purposes.

fields.title: Staff Parameters Players
fields.text:
Label: ID displayed to other people in an experiment.

Group: The group that this avatar is a member of.

Location: The starting location of this avatar in the environment.

Color: The color used to identify each person.

Instructions: The instruction set each person sees during the instruction phase and the associated help docs.

fields.title: Staff Parameters Notices
fields.text:
Text: On-screen text.

Start Period: The period the notice will start on.

Start Time: The time when the notice will show.

End Period: The period the notice will stop.

End Time: The time the notice will stop.

fields.title: Staff Parameters Walls
fields.text:
Info: Description of the wall location

Location: X/Y location of the top left corner of the wall.

Width: Width of the wall segment.

Height: Height of the wall segment.

fields.title: Staff Parameters grounds
fields.text:
Info: Description of the ground element.

Location: X/Y location of top left corner.

Width: Width of element in pixels.

Height: Height of element in pixels.

Tint: Colorize the element with a hex color.

Texture: Pre-loaded texture of element.

Rotation: Rotation in degrees of texture.

Scale: Scale of texture.

fields.title: Staff Parameters groups
fields.text: Players in the same group.

fields.title: Staff Parameters Barriers
fields.text:
Info: Description of the barrier.

Text: Text displayed to the subject on the barrier.

Text Rotation: Text rotation in degrees.

Blocked Groups: Groups that the barrier blocks from crossing.

Location: X/Y location of the top left corner.

Size: Width and Height of the barrier.

Period On/Off: The barrier activates and deactivates.

fields.text_html:
Welcome

This is an experiment in the economics of decision-making. The instructions are simple, and if you follow them carefully and make good decisions, you can earn a considerable amount of money that will be paid to you privately at the end of the experiment.

In this experiment, your name is #id_label#, and you are represented with the gear-shaped avatar in the center of your screen.

You and the other #player_count-1# people control an avatar that collects cherries. Cherries are converted to earnings at the end of each period.

1 cherry = #token_cents_value# ¢

Try navigating the environment now by left-clicking on the screen to locate your house. Do this now.

Continue to the next page of the instructions by pressing the Next   button.

Other Avatars

Your avatar can interact with other nearby avatars by right-clicking   on them. Move your avatar close to another avatar and interact with it. The other avatar must interact within the circle surrounding your avatar. You can send cherries from your avatar to other avatars. You can also take cherries from other avatars. During a "take" interaction, both your avatar and the other avatar are frozen in place. After a "take" interaction, your avatar and the other avatar are subject to a #cool_down_length#-second cool-down phase where neither can enage in a "take" interaction.

Walk over to another avatar and start an interaction. Do this now.

Continue to the next page of the instructions by pressing the Next   button.

Chat

You can chat with other nearby avatars using the chat box at the bottom of your screen. Do this now.

You are free to discuss any aspects of the experiment, with the following exceptions: you may not reveal your name, discuss side payments outside the laboratory, or engage in inappropriate language (including such shorthand as ‘WTF’). If you do, you will be excused and forgo your experiment earnings.

Every #break_frequency# periods has a #break_length#-second break phase, where chatting is enabled, but all other interactions are disabled.

Continue to the next page of the instructions by pressing the Next   button.

Conclusion

Many of the interaction menus have a help button  that you can use to reference the instructions during the experiment.

This is the end of the instructions. If you have any questions, please raise your hand, and a monitor will come by to answer them. If you are finished with the instructions, please click the Start   button located in the bottom right of this frame. The instructions will remain on your screen until the experiment begins. We need everyone to click the  Start   button before we can begin the experiment.
